06034nam a22009255i 9780691192611DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20192019nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97806911926117 a10.1515/97806911926112doi  a(DE-B1597)527617  a(OCoLC)1091847744  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aRA410.53b.P75 2019eb 7aBUS0330402bisacsh04a338.4/3362109732231 aReinhardt, Uwe E., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aPriced Out :bThe Economic and Ethical Costs of American Health Care /cUwe E. Reinhardt. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2019] 4cÂ©2019  a1 online resource (232 p.) :b55 b/w illus. 10 tables.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tForeword -- tForeword -- tPrologue -- tIntroduction -- tI. A Visual Stroll through America's Health Care Wonderland -- tII. Ethical Perspectives on U.S. Health Care -- tEpilogue -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFrom a giant of health care policy, an engaging and enlightening account of why American health care is so expensive-and why it doesn't have to beUwe Reinhardt was a towering figure and moral conscience of health care policy in the United States and beyond. Famously bipartisan, he advised presidents and Congress on health reform and originated central features of the Affordable Care Act. In Priced Out, Reinhardt offers an engaging and enlightening account of today's U.S. health care system, explaining why it costs so much more and delivers so much less than the systems of every other advanced country, why this situation is morally indefensible, and how we might improve it.The problem, Reinhardt says, is not one of economics but of social ethics. There is no American political consensus on a fundamental question other countries settled long ago: to what extent should we be our brothers' and sisters' keepers when it comes to health care? Drawing on the best evidence, he guides readers through the chaotic, secretive, and inefficient way America finances health care, and he offers a penetrating ethical analysis of recent reform proposals. At this point, he argues, the United States appears to have three stark choices: the government can make the rich help pay for the health care of the poor, ration care by income, or control costs. Reinhardt proposes an alternative path: that by age 26 all Americans must choose either to join an insurance arrangement with community-rated premiums, or take a chance on being uninsured or relying on a health insurance market that charges premiums based on health status.An incisive look at the American health care system, Priced Out dispels the confusion, ignorance, myths, and misinformation that hinder effective reform.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aHealth care reformzUnited States. 0aHealth insurancexLaw and legislationzUnited States. 0aHealth services accessibilityzUnited States. 0aMedical carezUnited States. 0aMedical care, Cost ofzUnited States. 0aMedical ethicszUnited States. 0aMedical policyzUnited States. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Insurance / Health.2bisacsh1 aCheng, Tsung-Mei, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCheng, Tsung-Mei.1 aFrist, Sen. William H.1 aFrist, William H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKrugman, Paul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKrugman, Paul.1 aReinhardt, Uwe E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019 Englishz978311061076508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe Gruy